---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '@/components/layout/SiteHeader.astro';
import SiteFooter from '@/components/layout/SiteFooter.astro';
import TangleCursor from '@/components/cursor/TangleCursor';

const lang = 'en';
const currentPath = '/en/about';
const title = 'Zentangle Chou — About Me';
const description = "YuChiao Chou's Zentangle Creative Journey";
---

<Layout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  lang={lang}
  currentPath={currentPath}
>
  <SiteHeader currentPath={currentPath} lang={lang} />

  <main class="flex-1">
    <!-- Hero -->
    <section class="py-20 px-4 bg-ink-50 dark:bg-ink-800">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto text-center">
        <h1 class="font-display-en text-4xl md:text-5xl text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-50 mb-6">
          Line by Line, Finding Stillness
        </h1>
        <p class="font-body text-lg text-ink-600 dark:text-ink-300">
          The Zentangle Journey of YuChiao Chou
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Main Content -->
    <section class="py-20 px-4">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <!-- Essay -->
        <article class="font-body text-ink-600 dark:text-ink-300 space-y-6 mb-20">
          <p class="text-base leading-relaxed">
            I first encountered Zentangle on a very hurried afternoon. My life was full of to-do lists, deadlines, and expectations from all directions—nothing ever seemed to finish. A friend handed me a 3.5-inch tile and a black pen, saying, "Try this. It only takes 30 minutes."
          </p>

          <p class="text-base leading-relaxed">
            Those 30 minutes changed something. Not in a dramatic, instant way, but rather a subtle, gradually spreading stillness—lines forming under my hand, one stroke after another, no eraser, no such thing as "wrong." I began to realize that completing a tile didn't require me to be brilliant or talented. It only required me to sit down and take one tangle at a time. That sense of permission felt like my first deep breath.
          </p>

          <p class="text-base leading-relaxed">
            Since then, I've been consciously collecting tiles. Each one is dated, marked with my mood at the time, sometimes with a few words. I've drawn in cafés, in late-night studios, in hotel corners while traveling. Some tiles become what I hoped they'd be; others don't. But regardless, they are all finished. In an age when tasks never seem to end, that sense of completion carries a special weight.
          </p>

          <p class="text-base leading-relaxed">
            Three years ago, I began studying Zentangle's deeper method—not just following tutorials, but understanding why Rick Roberts and Maria Thomas designed this system the way they did. I discovered that Zentangle doesn't ask you to empty your mind; rather, it invites you into a specific kind of focus: hand, eyes, and breath all aligned to the same moment. That is a form of inner stillness very few people ever feel.
          </p>

          <p class="text-base leading-relaxed">
            This website exists for one simple reason: I want to share. To share why these 41 patterns matter, how I apply them, and the stories of mistakes, experiments, and new beginnings. I also want friends, family, and the stranger who accidentally discovers the word "Zentangle" in a search engine, to see in one place someone who takes this practice seriously—who believes deeply in what it means.
          </p>
        </article>

        <!-- Timeline -->
        <div class="border-t border-ink-200 dark:border-ink-700 pt-12">
          <h2 class="font-display-en text-2xl text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-50 mb-12">
            Creative Milestones
          </h2>

          <div class="space-y-12">
            {[
              { year: '2022', title: 'First Encounter', desc: 'Discovered Zentangle and became captivated by its simplicity and depth.' },
              { year: '2023', title: 'Systematic Learning', desc: 'Began studying Rick & Maria\'s original method, completed hundreds of practice tiles.' },
              { year: '2024', title: 'Deep Exploration', desc: 'Researched 41 classic tangles, developed personal style and application combinations.' },
              { year: '2025', title: 'Sharing Plan', desc: 'Launched this website to share the practice of stillness with others.' },
            ].map(item => (
              <div key={item.year} class="flex gap-6">
                <div class="flex-shrink-0">
                  <span class="font-display-en text-2xl text-gold-500 dark:text-gold-400 font-bold">
                    {item.year}
                  </span>
                </div>
                <div>
                  <h3 class="font-display-en text-lg text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-50 mb-2">
                    {item.title}
                  </h3>
                  <p class="font-body text-sm text-ink-600 dark:text-ink-400">
                    {item.desc}
                  </p>
                </div>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Photo Grid Placeholder -->
    <section class="py-20 px-4 bg-ink-50 dark:bg-ink-800">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
        <h2 class="font-display-en text-2xl text-ink-700 dark:text-ink-50 mb-12 text-center">
          Photo Gallery
        </h2>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
          {[1, 2, 3, 4].map(i => (
            <div key={i} class="aspect-square bg-ink-200 dark:bg-ink-700 rounded-sm animate-pulse flex items-center justify-center">
              <p class="text-ink-400 dark:text-ink-500">Photo {i}</p>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <SiteFooter lang={lang} />
  <TangleCursor client:idle />
</Layout>
